---
description: Frontend slicing rule for converting approved designs into HTML using Bootstrap while preserving the current design system and SCSS architecture.
alwaysApply: true
---

You are working on a front-end project where a reference HTML page, Bootstrap usage pattern, and SCSS/style structure already exist.

You MUST strictly follow the existing design system, HTML structure, Bootstrap conventions, SCSS architecture, and project folder structure.

========================
1. DESIGN SYSTEM CONSISTENCY (STRICT)
========================
- The existing project design system is the single source of truth.
- Do NOT redesign any UI element.
- Do NOT introduce a new visual language.
- Match the current system in:
  - typography
  - spacing
  - colors
  - alignment
  - border radius
  - shadows
  - form styling
  - button styling
  - cards and tables
- Any generated page must look like it belongs to the SAME product and SAME design system.

========================
2. BOOTSTRAP USAGE (MANDATORY)
========================
- Use Bootstrap best practices in structure and layout.
- Prefer Bootstrap grid, utilities, spacing helpers, and responsive containers where appropriate.
- Reuse Bootstrap components in a clean and standard way.
- Do NOT misuse Bootstrap classes for purposes they were not intended for.
- Do NOT overload HTML with unnecessary utility classes when existing project classes already solve the problem.
- Keep Bootstrap usage maintainable, readable, and consistent with the current project style.

Rules:
- Prefer Bootstrap layout primitives first:
  - container / container-fluid
  - row / col-*
  - g-* spacing where suitable
  - d-flex / justify-content-* / align-items-* where suitable
- Use custom classes only when Bootstrap alone is insufficient or when matching the current project pattern.
- Do NOT replace existing project patterns with raw Bootstrap if the project already has a standardized wrapper/component structure.

========================
3. HTML STRUCTURE
========================
- Reuse the same layout structure already used in the project:
  - page wrappers
  - containers
  - sections
  - cards
  - forms
  - tables
  - modal structure
  - headers / footers / nav areas
- Keep DOM clean, semantic, and consistent.
- Do NOT introduce unnecessary wrappers or deeply nested div structures.
- Use semantic HTML whenever possible.
- Keep naming consistent with the current project conventions.

========================
4. EXISTING STYLES AND SCSS (CRITICAL)
========================
- Follow the existing SCSS structure strictly.
- Reuse existing:
  - variables
  - mixins
  - placeholders
  - utility classes
  - component classes
  - layout classes
- The current SCSS/style system must remain the foundation.
- Do NOT duplicate styles that already exist.
- Do NOT create a parallel styling system.
- Do NOT change the current design system behavior unless explicitly requested.

========================
5. PAGE-LEVEL STYLING RULE (MANDATORY)
========================
- If a generated page needs additional styling not already covered by the current shared styles:
  - you MAY create a page-specific SCSS file
  - and/or a page-specific CSS file
- These page-level files must be placed beside the generated HTML file in its folder.
- Only add the MINIMAL required page-level styles.
- Page-level styles must be small, targeted, and limited to the specific page.
- Do NOT move shared design rules into page-level files.
- Do NOT duplicate global styles into page-level files.
- Do NOT create page-level files unless they are actually needed.

Preferred approach:
1. Reuse existing shared styles first
2. Reuse Bootstrap utilities/components second
3. Add minimal page-specific SCSS/CSS only if necessary

========================
6. SCSS MODIFICATION RULE (MANDATORY)
========================
- You ARE allowed to:
  - add new styles
  - extend existing styles
  - make minimal updates to existing SCSS only when absolutely necessary

- BUT:
  - every addition MUST have a comment above it
  - every modification MUST have a comment above it
  - comments must clearly explain why the change was needed

Examples:
```scss
// [ADDED] Page-specific spacing for security inquiry summary section
.inquiry-summary {
  margin-top: 1.5rem;
}

// [UPDATED] Align card header spacing with approved design reference
.card-header {
  padding: $spacing-md $spacing-lg;
}
